A D J U D I C A T I O N
BACKGROUND:
This proceeding arises out of a citation that was issued on December 21, 2000, by the Bureau of Liquor Control Enforcement of the Pennsylvania State Police (hereinafter Bureau) against Samas, Inc., t/a The Wreck Room Bar 
The citation charges Licensee with violation of Section 471 of the Liquor Code [47 P.S. Â§4-471] and Section 5513 of the Crimes Code [18 Pa.
C.S. Â§5513], in that on March 18 and October 25, 2000, Licensee, by its servants, agents or employes, posssessed or operated gambling devices or paraphernalia or permitted gambling or lotteries, poolselling and/or bookmaking on the licensed premises.
The investigation which gave rise to the citation began on March 20, 2000 and was completed on November 15, 2000; and notice of the violation was sent to Licensee by Certified Mail on December 6, 2000.
An evidentiary hearing was held on this matter on May 8, 2001 in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
Upon review of the transcript of this hearing, we make the following Findings of Fact and reach the following Conclusions of Law:
FINDINGS OF FACT: 1.
Licensee is a corporation located in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania and holds Restaurant Liquor License Number R-AP-SS-6141.
(N.T. 4) 2.
On Saturday, March 18, 2000 at 9:05 p.m., an enforcement officer entered the licensed premises and found a barmaid heard to be called Missy rendering service of alcoholic beverages to 15 patrons.
(N.T. 6) 3.
At 9:10 p.m., the officer observed a female patron accumulate 40 credits on a table top Joker Poker video poker machine.
(N.T. 6-7) 4.
The patron notified the barmaid who cleared the credits from the video poker machine.
(N.T. 7) 5.
The barmaid removed $10.00 from the cash register and gave it to the patron.
(N.T. 7) 6.
Also on the premises, the officer observed one Cherry Master video poker machine, one Cherry Bonus video slot machine and one Lucky-8 Line video slot machine.
(N.T. 7) 7.
The patron placed U.S. currency into the table top video poker machine and continued playing.
(N.T. 7-8) 8.
On October 24, 2000, the enforcement officer obtained a search warrant for gambling devices at the licensed premises.
(N.T. 8-9) 9.
On Wednesday, October 25, 2000 at 3:40 p.m., the enforcement officer executed the search warrant of the licensed premises.
(N.T. 9) 10.
The enforcement officer seized one table top video poker machine and three Cherry Master video slot machines along with three video remote control devices used to knock off credits from the three slot machines.
(N.T. 11-12) 11.
The officer placed $1.00 into each machine and found them set up and operational.
(N.T. 10-11) 12.
On October 29, 2000 at 3:15 p.m., the enforcement officer examined the four seized video gambling machines and found that each accepted U.S. currency, required no skill to play, and had knock off circuitry and internal video accounting circuitry.
(N.T. 11-13) 13.
One of the video slot machines was damaged in transit and could not be inspected.
(N.T. 13)
CONCLUSION OF LAW:
Sustained as charged.
DISCUSSION:
At the hearing held on the matter, the enforcement officer testified in detail as to his visiting the premises on March 18, 2000 and observing Licensees barmaid make an illegal $10.00 gambling payoff to a patron who won 40 credits on a tabletop Joker Poker video poker machine.
On October 25, 2000, the video poker machine and three video slot machines were seized and subsequently found to be gambling devices per se.
Licensee did not appear at the hearing although duly notified of the place and time therof.
I find the testimony of the officer to be credible.
As such, the citation is sustained as charged.
PRIOR RECORD:
Licensee has been licensed since June 26, 1998, and has had no prior violations.
PENALTY:
Section 471 of the Liquor Code [47 P.S. Â§4-471] prescribes a penalty of license suspension or revocation or a fine of not less than $50.00 or more than $1,000.00 or both for violations of the type found in this case.
After due consideration of the circumstances giving rise to the citation, a $600.00 fine will be imposed.
Licensee is put on notice that it faces progressively harsh penalties for further violations of this type.
ORDER:
THEREFORE, it is hereby ordered that Licensee, Samas, Inc., t/a The Wreck Room Bar 
In the event the aforementioned fine is not paid within 20 days from the mailing date of this Order, Licensees license shall be suspended or revoked.
The fine must be paid by Treasurers Check, Cashiers Check, Certified Check or Money Order.
Personal checks, which include business-use personal checks, are not acceptable.
Please make guaranteed check payable to the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania and mail to:
PLCB - Office of Administrative Law Judge Brandywine Plaza 2221 Paxton Church Road Harrisburg, PA 17110-9661
